# Convert an SR sim to the GLOBAL DESIGN

You are upgrading one existing SR simulation HTML file to the shared global design.
These files ALREADY sit on an older engine shell (they have `#shell` with
`shell-header`/`shell-hero`/`shell-aside`/`shell-formal`, transport IDs, and a
`Shell` runtime). Your job is a **targeted upgrade**, not a rewrite.

## Reference material (read these first, every run)
- `_design-reference/reference-converted-sim.html` — a fully converted sim. This
  is the ground truth for markup, the Shell runtime, and the guided-inquiry stepper.
  **When anything below is ambiguous, copy from this file.**
- `_design-reference/SHELL-DESIGN-GUIDE.md` — the full spec (regions, runtime
  contract, stepper authoring, components, pedagogy rules).
- `_design-reference/simulation-shell.css` — the global stylesheet.

## THE #1 RULE — do not touch the science
- **NEVER change the physics or the canvas drawing.** The simulation's physics
  math, numerical methods, draw/render functions, equations, constants, and the
  canvas visuals must be **byte-for-byte identical** to the original. You only
  restructure the CHROME and MARKUP around them.
- **Do not change what controls exist or what they do.** Every slider, toggle,
  button, and readout in the original must still exist and behave identically —
  you only move it into its new home and restyle its wrapper.
- If you cannot make a design change without editing physics/draw code, STOP and
  leave that part as-is; note it in the report instead.

## Output
- Write a NEW file `<original-name>-shell.html` in the same folder. Never
  overwrite the original.
- End with a short **CONVERSION REPORT**: (1) what markup moved where, (2) the
  guided-inquiry steps you authored, (3) an explicit line confirming
  "physics/draw code unchanged," and (4) anything you could not do.

## Upgrade procedure

1. **Stylesheet + head.** Inline the full contents of
   `_design-reference/simulation-shell.css` into a `<style>` in `<head>` (so the
   file stays self-contained), OR `<link rel="stylesheet" href="_design-reference/simulation-shell.css">`
   if the user prefers linked. Keep the KaTeX `<link>`/`<script defer>`. Copy the
   base64 `<style data-sim-fonts>` block from the reference file into `<head>` so
   fonts embed. Ensure `<div id="shell" class="hide-formal">`.

2. **Swap in the NEW Shell runtime.** Replace the file's existing
   `const Shell = (function(){ … })();` block with the **verbatim** new runtime
   from the reference file (it owns the guided-inquiry stepper: dots, Next/Finish,
   Skip, collapse/restore, `onStep`). Do not edit it.

3. **Header (global controls only), canonical order:** title · `#shell-info` ·
   `#shell-theme` · `#shell-maximize` · `#toggle-formal` · Speed(`#shell-speed`) ·
   `#shell-reset` · `#shell-play`. If `#shell-theme` (☾ light/dark) is missing,
   ADD it beside Info (copy from reference). Remove any sim-specific control that
   crept into the header. Drop `∑ Formal` only if there is no formal region, and
   Speed only if there is no time-animation.

4. **Aside → the two-zone dynamic sidebar.** Replace the old aside contents with
   the reference's structure verbatim: `#aside-inquiry` (its head + `Skip ✕`, the
   empty `#inq-dots`, `#inq-cards` holding the step cards, and `#inq-next`), then
   `#aside-inquiry-restore`, then `#aside-controls`. You fill only `#inq-cards`
   and `#aside-controls`.

5. **Guided inquiry — convert the OLD prediction into step cards.** Take the
   sim's existing prediction (`pred` / `opt-btn` block) and its wording and turn
   it into a sequence of 4–6 `<div class="inq-step">` cards, fundamental → full:
   predict (gated, `data-gate`) → observe → verify (gated) → next layer/frame →
   resolve. Reuse the original question/answer/feedback text where it exists; only
   add cards to complete the arc. Encode the misconception as a wrong
   `<button class="choice" data-correct="0" data-fb="…">`; correct choice gets
   `data-correct="1"`. Add a `<div class="predict-eval"></div>` to each predict
   card. Add the generic prediction-feedback handler from the reference/guide to
   the SIM JS. Do NOT invent new physics claims — keep the pedagogy the sim already had.

6. **Controls + stats → design-system components.** Move the sim's sliders,
   toggles, and readouts into `#aside-controls` inside `.shell-panel` cards, using
   `.ctrl-box ctrl-box--slider` (slider), `.ctrl-box` + `.stat-row` (toggles/
   stats). Keep the SAME element IDs the sim's JS references (rename the wrappers,
   not the inputs) so no listener breaks. Keep every readout the sim shows.

7. **Hero.** Wrap each `<canvas>` in `<div class="plot-box">` with an optional
   `.plot-title` and `.legend`. Do not touch the canvas element's id or the draw code.

8. **Formal.** Move the equations into `.shell-formal` (`.formal-grid` of
   `.eq-row`). Keep KaTeX rendering but guard it for deferred load
   (`if(window.katex) render(); else window.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', render)`).

9. **Boot.** Ensure the SIM calls `Shell.init({ onFrame, onReset, onResize, onStep })`.
   Rewire ONLY the transport: the old rAF loop body becomes `onFrame(dt)` (dt is
   already speed-scaled), state-reset becomes `onReset()`, canvas re-fit becomes
   `onResize()`. Delete the sim's own play/pause/reset/speed/formal button
   handlers (the shell wires those). Everything else in the physics closure stays.

10. **Info modal.** Fill `#shell-info-modal`'s title + source/principles blocks
    from the sim's own metadata if present; otherwise keep the sim's existing info
    content. Never emit a literal `{{…}}` token.

## Self-check before finishing
- Loads with no console errors; canvas renders; Play toggles; every original
  slider/toggle still fires its handler; `Next` gates only on predict cards;
  `Finish` collapses the inquiry; Skip works; Maximize/Formal/Theme all present.
- The physics/draw code is unchanged from the original (diff them mentally).
- Design tokens (`var(--…)`) used for chrome; canvas colours left as the original had them.
